================================================================================
  2. THIRD-PARTY COMPONENTS  — Alloy 6 fetched at runtime, pinned to MiniSat
================================================================================

This repository does NOT redistribute any third-party binaries. The
Alloy 6 distribution is downloaded at runtime by
`skills/formal-modeling/scripts/alloy_run.sh` from the official
AlloyTools release on GitHub:

  https://github.com/AlloyTools/org.alloytools.alloy

The downloaded jar is extracted into a local, gitignored cache at
`skills/formal-modeling/scripts/.alloy/extracted/`. Those files are
governed by the licenses of their respective authors (see
THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES.md for the component-by-component breakdown);
the upstream `.txt` license files travel with the distribution inside
the `extracted/` directory and its `LICENSES/` subdirectory.

Pinned solver: the skill's `AlloyRunner` always uses MiniSat with
unsat-core support (kodkod solver id `minisat.prover`, MIT license),
with SAT4J (LGPL 2.1) as automatic fallback if the MiniSat native
library is unavailable on the current platform. The downloaded
distribution also contains Lingeling and ZChaff, but the skill
deliberately never invokes them.

Post-extraction strip: immediately after extracting the downloaded jar,
`alloy_run.sh` runs a `strip_nc_solvers` function that deletes the
Lingeling native binaries (`native/*/*/plingeling{,.exe}`, and the
`org/alloytools/solvers/natv/lingeling/` JNI wrapper package) from the
local cache. (ZChaff is not actually shipped as an executable solver
in Alloy 6.2+, only its historical license text remains.) After the
strip, the noncommercial solvers are not merely "never invoked" but
"physically absent" from the workspace.

Two separate reasons for the runtime-download + pinning pattern:

  1. ZChaff (Princeton) requires "prior consent of Princeton
     University" for any distribution. By fetching at runtime, each
     user invokes AlloyTools' own distribution channel directly —
     this repository never acts as a redistributor of ZChaff.
  2. Lingeling (Armin Biere) grants permission only for "evaluation
     and research purposes"; "all other usage is reserved." Same
     argument: not redistributed here, and never invoked by the
     skill regardless.

Alignment with this repository's CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license:

  - The skill is licensed NonCommercial. Downstream users must
    therefore be noncommercial, which aligns with the noncommercial
    restrictions on ZChaff and Lingeling if the user later chooses to
    enable them manually.
  - No obligation to redistribute flows from an LGPL 2.1 (SAT4J) or
    MPL 2.0 (Electrod) component to this repository, because this
    repository does not redistribute them — it merely instructs
    `alloy_run.sh` to download them.

Key constraints the user inherits when alloy_run.sh downloads the jar:

  - Alloy, Kodkod, MiniSat, JavaCup, Gini  — MIT.
  - SAT4J                                   — LGPL 2.1 (weak copyleft).
  - Electrod                                — MPL 2.0 (file-level
                                              copyleft).
  - Glucose / Syrup                         — MIT-base + no use in SAT
                                              competitions without the
                                              authors' permission.
  - ZChaff (Princeton)                      — noncommercial research
                                              use only; redistribution
                                              requires Princeton's
                                              consent (never invoked
                                              by this skill).
  - Lingeling (Biere)                       — "evaluation and research
                                              purposes" only; "all
                                              other usage is reserved"
                                              (never invoked by this
                                              skill).

